      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What type of protein is used in protein gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most protein gummies use one of three protein sources: (1) Whey protein isolate — the gold standard for bioavailability and amino acid profile, rapidly digested, with all essential amino acids including high leucine content for muscle protein synthesis. (2) Collagen peptides — derived from animal connective tissue, excellent for joint, skin, and gut health but incomplete in essential amino acid profile (low in leucine and tryptophan). (3) Plant protein blends — typically pea protein or soy protein isolate for vegan formulas, with complete amino acid profiles when properly combined. For weight loss, whey protein isolate is generally preferred for its superior satiety signaling and complete amino acid profile.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do protein gummies spike blood sugar?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'High-quality protein gummies with low sugar content (1-3g) and no added sugars do not cause significant blood sugar spikes. The protein content slows gastric emptying and reduces the glycemic impact of any carbohydrates present. However, some protein gummies contain sugar alcohols (maltitol, sorbitol, erythritol) as sweeteners — maltitol in particular has a glycemic index of 36 (vs. sugar at 65), meaning it does raise blood sugar moderately. Erythritol has a glycemic index of 0 and is the preferred sweetener for blood sugar management. Check the nutrition label for total sugar, added sugar, and sugar alcohol content.' },
    },
  ],
};
