    <h2 id="protein-weight-loss">Why Protein Gummies Are the Smartest Snack for Weight Loss</h2>

    <p>Weight loss fundamentally requires a calorie deficit, but the challenge is not math — it is hunger management. The reason most diets fail is not lack of willpower but the biological hunger signals that intensify as calorie intake drops. Protein is the most effective macronutrient for managing hunger: a 2015 meta-analysis in the <em>American Journal of Clinical Nutrition</em> demonstrated that protein intake of 25-30g per meal reduces overall daily caloric intake by suppressing ghrelin (the hunger hormone) and increasing peptide YY and GLP-1 (satiety hormones).</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">30%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">Of calories from protein are burned during digestion (thermic effect of food) — compared to <strong>5-10% for carbs and 0-3% for fat</strong>. This means protein is the most metabolically "expensive" macronutrient, further supporting weight loss beyond satiety alone.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Protein gummies occupy a unique niche in the weight loss supplement landscape: they deliver meaningful protein doses (10-15g) in a format that satisfies the craving for sweet, chewy treats — effectively replacing high-calorie candy and snack habits with a macronutrient that actively supports fat loss. A serving of traditional gummy bears contains 34g sugar and 140 calories with zero protein; a serving of protein gummies provides 10-15g protein at 60-120 calories with 0-3g sugar.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Satiety signaling</strong>
        <p>Protein stimulates PYY and GLP-1 release from intestinal L-cells, signaling fullness to the brain. This effect lasts 2-4 hours, bridging the gap between meals without caloric excess.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Thermic effect</strong>
        <p>30% of protein calories are burned during digestion — the highest TEF of any macronutrient. 100 calories of protein yields only 70 net calories after digestion.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
